            </span>
            <span class="utterance" who="#marcusH" start="1070.965" end="x">We lived under very hazardous conditions. As Jews . . . They took away our shoes, and we had to stand all night on a field barefoot. <a class="placename" href="#vothC69" type="camp">Majdanek</a> has a climate which has strong winds, unheard of, or great heats. Throughout the night a frost [snow?] of ten centimeters [ thick ] lay on the ground. They examined our feet, if we didn't put a piece of paper underneath. Afterwards, in the morning, we had to run, not walk, to work, chased after by a young female <a class="term" href="#vothG_ss">SS</a> man with a giant dog. Her name was Brigida.</span>
